Cape Town – Two friends who went swimming at Dappat Se Gat, between Gordons Bay and Kogelbaai, on Sunday ended up being caught in rip currents. While a 17-year-old was able to get ashore and was treated for hypothermia, his 19-year-old friend from Kuils River disappeared beneath the surf and is believed to have drowned. At 5.16pm on Sunday, the NSRI Gordons Bay duty crew were activated by the Transnet National Ports Authority (TNPA) following reports of a drowning in progress at Dappat Se Gat, NSRI Gordons Bay station commander Alan Meiklejohn said. "The sea rescue craft Spirit of Surfski was launched and an NSRI rescue vehicle, the SA Police Services, GB Med ambulance and rescue, CoCT (City of Cape Town) Fire and Rescue Services Dive Unit, CoCT Lifesaving lifeguards, WC Government Health EMS rescue squad and the EMS/AMS Skymed rescue helicopter responded. "On arrival on the scene, a search commenced for a 19-year-old male from Kuils River missing in the surf. "A 17-year-old male who had been swimming with his friend, the missing teenager, was found safe ashore and he was treated by paramedics for hypothermia and he required no further assistance. "Despite an extensive sea, air and shoreline search no sign of the missing teenager has been found and a police dive unit is continuing in an ongoing search operation." Police have opened an investigation and family of the missing teenager are being supported by police trauma counsellors. Cape Times 